missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:3:This chain has a real strength: it correctly sees that a fake theorem object should be killed early. The circularity check in Step 5 is especially useful. But as written, the chain is overly meta and risks producing a false negative for the mission by killing definitions before they are forced into contact with exact NS interaction structure.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:11:- The step asks for support, normalization, time window, and spectator size, but it omits several quantities that exact NS actually cares about: phase information, helical sign pattern, amplitude hierarchy, and whether "support" means single modes, conjugate pairs, or packets. That omission matters because triadic forcing depends on more than a support graph.
missions/exact-ns-no-near-closed-tao-circuit/planning-runs/run-001/attacks/chain-01.md:59:- The final kill condition only flags one kind of circularity: hard-coding Tao's averaged construction back into exact NS language. But circularity can also enter through tuned thresholds, cherry-picked time windows, or choosing a packet representation that predetermines leakage.
